# Design: Project Final Stabilization

## Technical Approach

Implement a **verification-only stabilization layer** with three bounded edits: (1) document one canonical full-suite contract at repo root, (2) align test/verification entrypoints in existing backend/frontend config so local and CI execute the same sequence, and (3) reduce known expected-error persistence noise only in test scope. This maps directly to spec requirements for reproducible contract, minimal noise hardening, and no runtime behavior changes.

## Architecture Decisions

| Decision | Options Considered | Tradeoffs | Decision |
|---|---|---|---|
| Canonical verification contract location | Root `README.md` vs separate runbook file | README is discoverable and already contributor entrypoint; separate file is cleaner but easier to miss | Add a dedicated “full-suite verification” section in `README.md` |
| Command orchestration style | New root script/task runner vs keep per-module native commands | New runner improves convenience but adds tooling and maintenance | Keep native `mvn` + `npm` commands; document strict sequence and pass/fail contract |
| Test-noise suppression scope | Global log suppression vs targeted test-profile filtering | Global suppression risks hiding regressions | Use test-only logging config and narrow package/signature filtering for known expected duplicates |

## Data Flow

Contributor/CI executes the same staged flow:

    Prerequisites check (Java/Node/npm)
            |
            v
    Backend verify (mvn test/verify)
            |
            v
    Frontend verify (npm test/lint/build)
            |
            v
    Contract outcome (all stages pass; failures include actionable guidance)

Noise-hardening path (test scope only):

    Expected duplicate-key test path
            |
            v
    Test logging filter matches known signature
            |
            v
    Reduce repeated non-actionable stack noise
            |
            +--> Assertions/failures unchanged and still visible

## File Changes

| File | Action | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `README.md` | Modify | Add canonical full-suite verification contract, prerequisites, exact command order, and expected outcomes. |
| `backend/pom.xml` | Modify (if needed) | Keep/clarify verify lifecycle consistency for CI-local parity (no production plugin/runtime change). |
| `frontend/package.json` | Modify (if needed) | Keep/clarify scripts used by canonical contract (`test`, `lint`, `build`) and naming consistency only. |
| `backend/src/test/resources/application-test.yml` | Modify | Add test-profile logging controls for expected persistence-noise signatures only. |
| `backend/src/test/resources/logback-test.xml` | Create (if needed) | Centralize narrow test-only logger filters/levels to reduce repeated expected error noise. |
| `backend/src/test/java/**` | Modify (small, if needed) | Tag/shape noisy expected-error tests so filters apply predictably without changing assertions. |

## Interfaces / Contracts

No API/domain contract changes.

Verification contract (documentation-level):

```text
Preconditions:
- Java 21 available
- Node/npm versions documented in repo contract

Execution order:
1) backend: mvn test (or mvn verify where applicable)
2) frontend: npm test
3) frontend: npm run lint
4) frontend: npm run build

Pass contract:
- Every stage exits 0
- Failures must expose actionable prerequisite or test failure output
```

## Testing Strategy

| Layer | What to Test | Approach |
|---|---|---|
| Unit | Existing backend/frontend unit behavior remains unchanged | Re-run existing unit suites with no assertion updates unrelated to noise control |
| Integration | Known expected duplicate/error paths still assert same outcomes | Run targeted Spring integration tests that intentionally trigger duplicates; verify pass/fail semantics unchanged |
| E2E/Full-suite | Reproducible contract local vs CI | Execute documented end-to-end command sequence on clean setup and compare stage outcomes |

## Migration / Rollout

No migration required. Rollout is immediate via docs + test/config changes only. If instability appears, revert stabilization artifacts without affecting production behavior.

